  </div>
</section>

<h2>What's in it</h2>
<p>Two datasets, normalised on <code>mark_id</code>:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Marks</strong> &mdash; the reference points (the metadata). One small JSON per decision: the setup,
      the effect as an honest distribution, the validity evidence it passed, and full provenance.</li>
  <li><strong><code>episodes</code> dataset</strong> &mdash; the per-unit rows behind every mark, unioned into one
      <em>(state, action, reward)</em> table for model training. A single Parquet, joined back to each mark on <code>mark_id</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>You can check two things against a mark: does your model get the <strong>effect</strong> right, and is its <strong>confidence</strong> honest?</p>

<h2>Coverage</h2>
<div class="cards">
  {{range .Marks}}
  <div class="card">
    <span class="domain">{{.Domain}} · {{.UnitType}}</span>
    <h3>{{.Series}}</h3>
    <p>{{.Estimand}}</p>
    <span class="effect">Effect {{.EffectStr}}</span>
    <a class="more" href="dossiers/{{.ID}}.html">Read the dossier &rarr;</a>
  </div>
  {{end}}
</div>

<h2>The finding it's built to show</h2>
<p>A method that reports only its <em>sampling</em> error looks confident but is wrong too often &mdash; it ignores
   how much the answer depends on modelling choices. A method that accounts for that is honestly less certain, and
   better calibrated. In the committed calibration study, at a nominal 95% interval the plug-in method covers the
   truth only <strong>{{.PlugInCov}}</strong> of the time; the model-averaged method <strong>{{.SBICov}}</strong>.</p>
